The CJMCU-1808 has a total of 28 pins, which are distributed as follows:

* VCC (1): Power supply input (Typically 3.3V or 5V)
* GND (2-4): Ground connections (3 pins)
* DOUT (5-16): Data output bus (12 bits)
* DIN (17-20): Data input bus (4 bits)
* CS# (21): Chip Select input (active low)
* SCLK (22): Serial clock input (SPI interface)
* RES (23): Reset input (active low)
* INT (24): Interrupt output (push-pull driver)
* PENIRQ (25): Pen interrupt input (interrupt when stylus touches screen)
* X+ (26), X-, Y+, Y- (27-30): Analog inputs for touchscreen coordinates

**Specs:**

* Resolution: Up to 12-bit resolution for each coordinate (4096x4096 points)
* Touch type: Capacitive or resistive touch screens supported (switchable via software)
* Interface: SPI (Serial Peripheral Interface) with maximum speed of 10 MHz (divisible by 2/4/8)
* Sampling rate: Up to 100 Hz (programmable)
* Current consumption:
	+ Active mode: Typically 250 uA (@3.3V, @25°C)
	+ Sleep mode: Typically 50 nA (@3.3V, @25°C)

Keep in mind that these details might not be comprehensive, as the chip may have additional features or configurations not mentioned here.

* X+ (7): Analog input for X-axis positive terminal (touch screen connection)

* Y+ (9): Analog input for Y-axis positive terminal (touch screen connection)
* Y- (10): Analog input for Y-axis negative terminal (touch screen connection)

**Specifications:**

* Supply Voltage: 2.7V to 5.5V DC (typical operating voltage: 3.3V)
* Input/Output voltage: CMOS compatible (TTL logic level)
* Communication Interface:
	+ I²C bus compatible (master/slave mode)
	+ Support multiple master devices on the same I²C bus (Slave address: 0x48)
* Resolution: 12 bits (X, Y coordinates)
* Conversion Time: < 30μs typical at 3.3V supply voltage and 400kHz I²C clock frequency.
